# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The **12-pounder long gun** was an intermediary calibre piece of artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] They were used as main guns on the most typical frigates of the early 18th century, on the second deck of fourth-rate ships of the line, and on the upper decks or castles of 80-gun and 120-gun ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Naval 12-pounders were similar to 12-pound Army guns in the Gribeauval system: the canon lourd de 12 Gribeauval, used as a siege weapon, and the canon de 12 Gribeauval, which was considered a heavy field artillery piece.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] As the 12-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, it was a widespread gun amongst nations between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XIV, frigates were organised into "first-rank frigates", which were small two-deckers comparable in role to the 60-gun ships of the 19th century, and smaller "second-rank" frigates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The first-rank frigates carried the 12-pounder as main artillery on their lower deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Later, under Louis XV, the frigate took its modern shape with a single artillery deck complemented by smaller pieces on the castles; new heavy frigates were developed to carry 26 12-pounders, with *Hermione* as the lead ship of the series.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] *Hermione* was captured by the British in 1757 and was swiftly imitated.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] A breakthrough towards fielding heavier guns was made in 1772, when the two units of the *Pourvoyeuse* class were built, with 24-pounders intended, but 18-pounders used in practice, and the 12-pounder remained the standard issue on most units.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XVI, the heavier 18-pounder frigate became predominant, with over 130 units produced, but the French Navy still had around 70 lighter 12-pounder frigates in commission.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] On 64-gun two-deckers, the 12-gun was used as secondary artillery, to supplement the 24-pounder main batteries.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] 28 guns were carried on the top gun-deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Larger units used the 12-pounder to complement the firepower provided by their main and secondary artillery.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] On 80-gun ships of the *Tonnant* class and *Bucentaure* class, they armed the forecastle and the poop deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] On capital ships, the 12-pounder was used on the third deck from the reign of Louis XIV, with units like *Royal Louis* or *Soleil Royal* as typical examples.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] While the secondary artillery of these 100-gun ships evolved from 18-pounders to 24-pounders, the 12-pounder remained the standard gun on the third deck until 1803, when the *Océan*-class ship *Impérial* became the first 120-gun to carry 18-pounders on her third battery.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, the 12-pounder was used in a similar capacity.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The capture of *Hermione* in 1757 encouraged the British to imitate her design, yielding the *Southampton* and *Richmond*-class frigates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The 12-pounder also equipped the castles on razeed ships, where 12 pieces were mounted, and the 22-gun secondary battery of 50-gun fourth-rates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Finally, 30 were installed on the third deck of 90-gun second-rates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] James mentions 4 12-pounder iron guns in the 1720s.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] 24 guns from the reigns of Queen Anne and King George I survive at Fort Prince of Wales in Hudson bay.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] They are either 9 1/2 ft long weighing between 33 1/2 and 35 cwt, 9 ft long weighing between 32 and 33 1/2 cwt, or 8 ft long weighing 33 1/4 cwt.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The mensuration of 1743 gives the weight of the 9 ft 12-pounder gun as 32 hundredweight 2 quarter 3 pounds, and the dimensions there are almost identical with those in Adye's notebook of 1766.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] In 1780 Walton's notebook mentions, in addition to newer 12-pounders, a 9 1/2 ft gun of 34 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The dimensions of this are very similar to those of Armstrong's construction in the early 1700s.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Walton gives dimensions for these guns in his 1780 notebook, and where known, they are very similar to the earlier guns, with only minor differences.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] Both guns of 6 ft were intended exclusively for the land service, and by 1857 the gun of 6 ft 21 hundredweight was the only one mounted in service, presumably in the defense of ditches.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 8 1/2 ft 33 1/4 hundredweight was recommended for siege trains in 1844, as it could dismount artillery while requiring less weight of ammunition and powder than an 18- or 24-pounder gun.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] At the same time, the gun of 9 ft 34 3/4 hundredweight was recommended for sometimes replacing the 18-pounder in batteries where quick fire was required against storming parties or boat attacks.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] After the 1820s, the development of larger guns meant the iron 12-pounder declined in use, and in 1859 the Committee on Ordnance recommended that all iron 12-pounders except the gun of 6 ft be declared obsolete.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] In 1865 though, the guns of 9 and 8 1/2 ft were retained while all others were declared obsolete.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/12-pounder-long-gun] "British Smooth-Bore Artillery: A Technological Study to Support Identification, Acquisition, Restoration, Reproduction, and Interpretation of Artillery at National Historic Parks in Canada" (PDF). pp.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The **18-pounder long gun** was an intermediary calibre piece of naval artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] They were used as main guns on the most typical frigates of the early 19th century, on the second deck of third-rate ships of the line, and even on the third deck of late first-rate ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] As the 18-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, it was used in many European navies between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] It was a heavy calibre for early ships of the line, arming, for instance, the main batteries of *Couronne* in 1636.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 18-pounder in three capacities: as the main gun on frigates, as the battery on the upper gundeck of two-deckers, and lastly on the top deck of three-deckers.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] French frigates began carrying the 18-pounder under Louis XV, when the two *Pourvoyeuse*-class frigates, originally designed to carry 24-pounders, were equipped with it; at the time, a typical frigate would carry 12-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XVI, from 1779, the 18-pounder gradually became the standard calibre for frigates, starting with the *Hébé* class.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] These frigates were built on standard patterns designed by Jacques-Noël Sané, carrying 26, and later 28 main guns, complemented with smaller pieces on the forecastle.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Around 130 of these frigates were built.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] At the end of the First French Empire, 24-pounder frigates began supplanting the 18-pounder frigates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Frigates built after the Bourbon Restoration used a different artillery system, one involving 30-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] On two-deckers, the 18-pounder was mounted on the upper deck as secondary artillery, to complement the 36-pounder main artillery on the lower deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] A 74-gun would carry thirty 18-pounders; this lighter secondary battery added firepower to the ship without raising the centre of gravity too much.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Three-deckers used 36-pounders on their lower decks and 24-pounders on their second deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 18-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] After introduction of rifled artillery in the middle 19th century, long 18-pounders were converted into so-called "14 cm n° 1 rifled muzzle-loaders Model 1864", by etching grooves on the inside of the barrel.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] James mentions 6 different 18-pounder guns in the early 1720s.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 ft appears in a diagram from about 1735, where its weight was listed as 41 hundredweight 1 quarter 8 pounds.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The 1743 mensuration contains an 18-pounder of the same length and weight, with very similar dimensions.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] In tests in Minorca, one of the 18-pounders used was 9 ft long and weighed 39 hundredweight 1 quarter 3 pounds.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] 3 guns of 9 feet length from the reign of George II (1727–1760) currently survive at the Gut of Digby in Nova Scotia.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Their dimensions are similar to the gun in the 1735 diagram.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's notebook from 1766 has an 18-pounder of 9 ft with almost identical dimensions to that in the 1735 diagram and 1743 mensuration.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The establishment of 1764 mentioned an 18-pounder gun of 9 ft and 40 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Walton included a gun with this length and weight in his table of dimensions in 1780, with similar dimensions to the 9 ft gun in the 1743 mensuration and the 1766 notebook.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813 mention the 9 ft 40 hundredweight 18-pounder, though by then it was being superseded by the newer Blomefield guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9+1⁄2 ft is mentioned in Walton's table of dimensions in 1780, where its weight was 42 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] It also appears in Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813, when it was also being superseded by Blomefield pattern guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 11 ft is first mentioned in tests in Minorca, where its weight was given as 51 hundredweight 5 pounds.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1820, 6 iron 18-pounders are mentioned, with weights from 50 to 54+1⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1857, an 18-pounder of 11 ft, "O.P" (old pattern) was in the list of guns submitted to the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight and 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight were widely used as siege and garrison guns in addition to their naval role.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] As a siege gun, the 18-pounder served the same role as the Canon de 16 Gribeauval.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight was used on the upper deck of 74-gun ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight was used on the main deck of 46- and 42-gun frigates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1825 Mould noted the gun of 6 feet 27 hundredweight was "not used at present." Although the guns of 6 feet 20 hundredweight and 5+1⁄2 feet 15 hundredweight were bored-up from Blomefield guns, an 1865 report mentions that they were designed by Alexander Dickson (Blomefield's successor).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] William Congreve designed an 18-pounder gun patterned after his 24-pounder gun, after the latter proved successful in trials in 1813.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] It was 6 feet 10 inches in length and 32 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] It had the same conical shape with more metal around the breech, and trunnions further to the rear.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] 8 pieces were mentioned in lists submitted to the Committee on Ordnance in 1857, though it may have only been experimental.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns retained were Blomefield or Dickson pattern guns mentioned above, as were the guns of 6 feet and 7 feet to be abolished.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 6 feet 10 inches was a Congreve gun.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 40 hundredweight is not known, but it may have been the old 18-pounder of 9 feet from the establishment of 1764.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] The Royal Navy used the 18-pounder on frigates, which carried 28 guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 26 on their secondary batteries, and third rates carried 28.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] Unlike the French, the British used second rates, of 90 to 98 guns; the 90-gun vessels carried thirty 18-pounders on their middle deck, while the 98-gun vessels carried a total of sixty 18-pounders, distributed over both the second and the third deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/18-pounder-long-gun] First rates carried thirty-four 18-pounders on their third deck and 24-pounders on the middle deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The **24-pounder long gun** was a heavy calibre piece of artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were in service in the navies of France, Spain, Great Britain, the Netherlands, Sweden, and the United States.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] They were comparable to the Canon de 24 Gribeauval used by the French Army as its largest piece of siege artillery.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were used as main guns on the heaviest frigates of the early 19th century and on fourth-rate ships of the line, on the second deck of first-rate ships of the line, and on the second deck of a few large third-rates.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The 24-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, and was a widespread gun amongst nations between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 24-pounder in two capacities: as main gun on frigates and 64-guns, or as secondary artillery on three-deckers and even enlarged versions two-deckers.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The experiment was tried again in 1785 with *Pomone*, a successful design that opened the way to a standardisation on the 24-pounder frigate exemplified by the *Romaine* class.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Overall, 14 of these heavy frigates were built between *Pomone* in 1785, and *Poursuivante* in 1798, each carrying between 24 and 30 24-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] After the Bourbon Restoration, frigates were built using a different artillery system, carrying 30-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Two-deckers used the 24-pounder in two capacities: on the smallest two-deckers of 64 guns, the 24-pounder constituted the main artillery, with 26 pieces.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Typical 74-gun vessels carried a 36-pounder main battery and an 18-pounder secondary battery, until the enlarged variant of the *Téméraire* class appeared in 1803, comprising *Vétéran* and *Cassard*.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] More significantly, the 24-pounder armed the secondary battery of all 80-gun ships of the line from 1749, when the *Soleil-Royal* introduced the practice, resulting in a two-decker with enough firepower to challenge a three-decker of the time.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] During the reign of Louis XIV, three-deckers were standardised on a 36-pounder main artillery and an 18-pounder secondary battery.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] From the mid-18th century, under Louis XV, the secondary battery was strengthened to 24-pounders, beginning with the *Sans-Pareil* design that yielded *Royal Louis*.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The other capital ships of the era, *Ville de Paris*, flagship of François Joseph Paul de Grasse during the American War of Independence, and *Bretagne*, flagship at the Battle of Ushant, similarly carried 24-pounders as secondary batteries.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The practices was continued with the *Océan* class and the *Commerce de Paris* class.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 24-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, the 24-pounder was similarly used on some heavy frigates, which carried 26 guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 22 on their secondary batteries, and third-rates carried 32.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] First-rates carried thirty-four 24-pounders on their middle deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Ten surviving guns which are likely examples of the 91⁄2-foot version weigh between 48 and 493⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] These guns are very similar to the gun of 91⁄2 feet and 491⁄4 hundredweight which was detailed in the mensuration of 1743.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] One other 24-pounder is mentioned in sources from 1780 and later, specifically a gun of 10 feet and 52 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] It is unknown whether the gun was new or the same as the 10 foot 24-pounder mentioned above.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Except the guns of 501⁄2, 473⁄4, 22, and 20 hundredweight, most of these guns were little used, and declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns cast in 1813 were designed to be evaluated against William Congreve's new pattern of gun.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 91⁄2 feet 501⁄2 hundredweight and 9 feet 473⁄4 hundredweight were highly regarded as siege guns and widely used in that role in addition to their naval use.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 22 and 20 hundredweight were mostly used in casemates and flank defenses as replacements for 24-pounder carronades.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] In response to a desire for lighter 24-pounders that could still be double-shotted,William Congreve designed a radical new type of 24-pounder, which was shorter, lighter, and with more metal concentrated around the gun breech rather than the chase (gun barrel).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] It had a muzzle similar to a carronade, and the breeching ring was discarded in favor of a hole in the center of the neck of the cascabel.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Because the weight of the cannon was much farther back, the trunnions could also be cast much farther rearward than in a similar conventional cannon.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The heavier gun was tested in HMS *Eurotas* in October 1813, and the lighter gun was tested on HMS *Pactolus* in February 1814.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] The results were so favorable (despite somewhat violent recoil) that 300 more guns were ordered, and by 1820, Congreve noted 700 guns as being cast.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve also suggested several other guns to be constructed according to his principle, including a 24-pounder of 8 feet and 50 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] However, the recoil of the guns when in service proved to be worse than the trials indicated, and they were withdrawn from service by 1830, except in East India Company service.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] That year, 800 24-pounders were bored-up to produce 32-pounders, and they remained in active service in that role past 1865.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve's other suggested guns were never used beyond the testing stage.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] These were similar to the Blomefield designs, but with a slightly smaller caliber of 5.792 instead of 5.823 inches.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] In addition, a number of guns designated "N.P." for New Pattern appear in the records of the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Finally, a 24-pounder of either 4 ft 10 in (1.47 m) or 5 ft (1.5 m) and 18 cwt was mentioned, and it was declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Images are available showing 24-pounder long guns as the main gun deck armament on the USS *Independence* as used during the American Revolution; and the USS *Constitution* and USS *Constellation* as two of the original six frigates of the United States Navy starting in 1797.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] From the War of 1812 until the 1840s, The U.S.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] Navy used three classifications: the gun proper, which had a barrel weight of 150 lb (68 kg) per pound of shot, the double-fortified gun which had a barrel weight of 200 lb (91 kg) per pound of shot, and the medium gun, which had a barrel weight of 100 lb (45 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/24-pounder-long-gun] By comparison, a carronade would have a barrel weight of 65 lb (29 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] The **demi-cannon** was a medium-sized cannon, similar to but slightly larger than a culverin and smaller than a regular 42 pounds (19 kg) cannon, developed in the early 17th century.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] A full cannon fired a 42-pound shot, but these were discontinued in the 18th century as they were seen as too unwieldy.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] The lower tiers of 18th century English warships were usually equipped with demi-cannons.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] Ships featuring demi-cannons included *Sovereign of the Seas*, *Resolution* and *James*, which fought in the Anglo-Dutch naval wars.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] Demi-cannons were also used on HMS *Stirling Castle*, the wreck of which was discovered in the Goodwin Sands.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] Several examples of this weapon were recovered from the site.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] The barrels of demi-cannon were typically 11 feet (3.4 m) long, had a calibre of 6 inches (150 mm) and could weigh up to 5,600 pounds (2,500 kg).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] It required 18 pounds (8.2 kg) of black powder to fire a 32 pounds (15 kg) round shot.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] The demi-cannon had an effective range of 1,600 feet (490 m).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] These 32-pounders were used during the 18th century on first-rate ships of the line which carried up to 100 guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] Though powerful, the naval demi-cannons were inaccurate, except at close range, which allowed warships to cause as much damage as possible.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/32-pounder-long-gun] Sometimes a single broadside was enough to cripple the enemy vessel.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] The **36-pounder long gun** was the largest piece of artillery mounted on French warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] They were also used for coastal defense and fortification.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] They largely exceeded the heaviest guns fielded by the Army, which were 24-pounder long guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] The nominal weight of shot was 36 French *livres*, 17.6 kg (38.8 lb).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] Installed on the lower deck of the larger warships, the 36-pounder long gun was the largest caliber used in the Navy of the Age of the Sail.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] Attempts to use 48-pounders were made, for instance on *Royal Louis*, but these proved impractical to use on ships, partly because their weight allowed for only a few pieces, and because the heavy balls were unwieldy to load by hand.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] However, some coastal batteries fielded 48-pounders and even 64-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, a similar role was fulfilled by 32-pounder long guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] French warships began to carry 36-pounders under Louis XIV, with the reform of the Navy undertaken by Richelieu.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] At this time, only first rank warships could carry them.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] In 1676, the entire Navy fielded merely 64 such heavy pieces, all bronze.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] From 1690, in only two years, their number increased from 115 to 442 (of which 407 were made of bronze), as the number and size of first-rank ships increased.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] Many 12-pounders were melted to procure the bronze needed to produce the needed 36-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] A maximum was reached in 1702 with 860 guns (411 bronze and 449 iron).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XV, their number was significantly reduced (164 in 1718, 452 in 1741), but from the mid-18th century, a sustained rearmament effort increased the number of 36-pounders to 986 in 1756, 1046 in 1777 and 2484 in 1786.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] They armed the lower battery of the largest warships: a 74-gun ship of the line would carry 28; an 80-gun, 30; and both 110-gun and 120-gun, 32.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] After the Napoleonic Wars, the 36-pounder long gun remained in use on older warships, though it was largely superseded by the 30-pounder long gun on newer units.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] The 36-pounders of the 1820s were fitted with flintlock primers, and those produced in this era featured a characteristic ring on the pommel.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] A 36-pounder required a 14-man crew, comprising one chief gunner, 12 gunners, and one powder boy.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] To load the piece, the first left-hand gunner would introduce a cartridge into the barrel; the first right-hand gunner would ram it to the bottom of the barrel; the first left-hand gunner would introduce the shot and a cloth wad, which would be rammed by the right-hand gunner.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] Then the crew would bring the gun to bear by pulling ropes.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] The chief gunner would then pin the cartridge through the touch hole and pour priming powder.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] The chief gunner would then point the gun with the help of the third and fourth gunners on each side, and the last gunner on the left would then fire the gun by touching the touch hole with a linstock.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] Flintlock firing was not standardized in the French navy before the end of the First Empire.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/36-pounder-long-gun] The first right-hand gunner would then ram thrice to remove residues from the bore of the gun.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/8-pounder-long-gun] The **8-pounder long gun** was a light calibre piece of artillery mounted on French warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/8-pounder-long-gun] It fired a projectile of eight *livres* in weight, equivalent to 8.633 English pounds, or 8 lb 10 oz (the French *livre* was 7.916% heavier than the English pound weight).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/8-pounder-long-gun] They were used as chase guns or main guns on light ships of the early 19th century, and on the quarterdeck and forecastle of ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/8-pounder-long-gun] They were similar in design to the Canon de 8 Gribeauval.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/8-pounder-long-gun] The 8-pounder was the heaviest of the light guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/8-pounder-long-gun] This made it useful as a chase gun, since its load packed enough power to damage the rigging of a fleeing enemy (if used as a bow chaser) or of a pursuing enemy (when used as a stern chaser).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The Age of Sail encompasses the period of roughly 1571–1862, when large, sail-powered wooden naval warships dominated the high seas, mounting a large variety of types and sizes of cannon as their main armament.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] By modern standards, these naval artillery pieces were extremely inefficient, difficult to load, and short ranged.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] These characteristics, along with the handling and seamanship of the ships that mounted them, defined the environment in which the naval tactics in the Age of Sail developed.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Firing a naval cannon required a great amount of labour and manpower.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The propellant was gunpowder, whose bulk had to be kept in the magazine, a special storage area below deck for safety.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] *Powder boys*, typically 10–14 years old, were enlisted to run powder from the magazine up to the gun decks of a vessel as required.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A wet swab was used to mop out the interior of the barrel, extinguishing any embers from a previous firing which might set off the next charge of gunpowder prematurely.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Gunpowder was placed in the barrel, either loose or in a cloth or parchment cartridge pierced by a metal 'pricker' through the touch hole, and followed by a cloth wad (typically made from canvas and old rope), then rammed home with a rammer.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Next the shot was rammed in, followed by another wad to prevent the cannonball from rolling out of the barrel if the muzzle was depressed.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The gun in its carriage was then 'run out'; men heaved on the gun tackles until the front of the gun carriage was hard up against the ship's bulwark, the barrel protruding out of the gun port.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] This took the majority of the gun crew manpower, as the weight of a large cannon in its carriage could total over two tons, and the ship would probably be rolling.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The touch hole in the rear (breech) of the cannon was primed with finer gunpowder (priming powder) or from a quill (from a porcupine or the skin-end of a feather) pre-filled with priming powder, then ignited.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The earlier method of firing a cannon was to apply a linstock—a wooden staff holding a length of smoldering match at the end—to the touch-hole of the gun.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] This was dangerous and made accurate shooting difficult from a moving ship, as the gun had to be fired from the side to avoid its recoil, and there was a noticeable delay between the application of the linstock and the gun firing.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] In 1745, the British began using *gunlocks* (flintlock mechanisms fitted to cannon).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The gunlock, by contrast, was operated by pulling a cord or lanyard.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The gun lock was a larger version of the flintlock mechanism used on pistols and muskets and was screwed onto the gun, next to the ignition vent.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The gun-captain could stand behind the gun, safely beyond its range of recoil, and sight along the barrel, firing when the roll of the ship lined the gun up with the enemy, and so reduce the chance of the shot hitting the sea or flying high over the enemy's deck.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Despite their advantages, gunlocks spread gradually as they could not be retrofitted to older simple fuse cannons, due to their large difference in design and operation.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The British adopted them faster than the French, who had still not generally adopted them by the time of the Battle of Trafalgar (1805), placing them at a disadvantage, as the new technology was in general use by the Royal Navy at this time.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] After the introduction of gunlocks, linstocks were retained, but only as a backup means of firing.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The linstock slow match or the spark from the flintlock ignited the priming powder, which in turn set off the main charge, which propelled the shot out of the barrel.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] When the gun discharged, the recoil sent it backwards until it was stopped by the breech rope, a sturdy rope made fast to ring bolts let into the bulwarks, with a turn taken about the gun's cascabel (the knob at the end of the gun barrel).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A typical broadside of a Royal Navy ship of the late 18th century could be fired 2–3 times in approximately 5 minutes, depending on the training of the crew, a well trained one being essential to the process of preparing to fire.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The British Admiralty did not see fit to provide additional powder to captains to train their crews.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Instead of live fire practice, many captains exercised their crews by "running" the guns in and out, performing all the steps associated with firing but without the actual discharge.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] This lack of gunnery training is attributed as being one of the main reasons the Royal Navy suffered such heavy losses to the United States Navy during the War of 1812.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Some wealthy captains, those who had made money capturing prizes or who came from wealthy families, were known to purchase powder with their own funds to enable their crews to fire real discharges at real targets.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A complete and accurate listing of the types of naval guns requires analysis both by nation and by time period.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The types used by different nations at the same time often were very different, even if they were labelled similarly.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The types used by a given nation would shift greatly over time, as technology, tactics, and current weapon fashions changed.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] In 1712, Colonel Albert Borgard was appointed to the head of the British Royal Ordnance, and introduced a new method of classification by which guns were defined by their **pound** rating — theoretically, the weight of a single solid iron shot fired by that bore of cannon.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] French ships used similarly standardized caliber guns of 36-pound, 24-pounders, 18-pounders, 12-pounders, and 8-pounders, augmented by carronades and smaller pieces.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The word *pound* in this context refers to the French pre-metric unit of weight - the *livre*, which was 7.916 percent more than the English/British equivalent; thus, as an example, the French "36-pounder" actually equated in British terms to 38lb 13.6oz.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A similar qualification must be placed on references to size of guns (i.e. weight of projectile) for every other nation, since each country had its own system of weights and measures.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The Spanish "pound", or *libra*, as another example, equated to 0.4608 kg (1.016 lb) (the British pound equals 0.4536 kg (1.000 lb)); and thus the Spanish 36-libra projectile actually weighed 36lb 9.143oz in British measurements.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] In general, larger ships carried more guns and the guns they carried were of a larger calibre.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The muzzle-loading design and weight of the iron placed design constraints on the length and size of naval guns.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Muzzle-loading required the cannon to be positioned within the hull of the ship for loading.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The hull width, guns lining both sides, and hatchways in the centre of the deck also limited the room available.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Weight is always a great concern in ship design as it affects speed, stability, and buoyancy.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The desire for longer guns for greater range and accuracy, and greater weight of shot for more destructive power, led to some interesting gun designs.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] One of the more unique naval guns, in terms of use, was the **long nine**, with its use dating back to at least 1660.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] It was a long-barrelled 9-pound gun (4.2 in (110 mm)) with a barrel length of either 7 (2.13 meters), 8 (2.43 meters), or 9 feet (2.74 meters).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The long nine was one of the few types of cannons known to be mounted as a bow or stern chaser where it was not perpendicular to the keel, and this also allowed room to operate this longer weapon.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] In a chase situation, the gun's greater range came into play.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] However, the desire to reduce weight in the ends of the ship and the relative fragility of the bow and stern portions of the hull limited this role to a 9-pounder, rather than one which used a 12- or 24-pound shot.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The long nine fell out of use in the early 18th century, but saw a resurgence in the second half of the century on small to medium size warships.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The long nine was also used as the main battery for certain classes of warship.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] In 1761, the British Royal Ordnance Board authorized the 7 foot long nine for use as a main battery gun on 24-gun (or fewer) Sixth-rate frigates, and the 9 foot for use on the upper deck batteries of 80-gun Third-rate Ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The **carronade** was another compromise design.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] It fired an extremely heavy shot but, to keep down the weight of the gun, it had a very short barrel, giving it shorter range and lesser accuracy.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] However, at the short range of many naval engagements, these "smashers" were very effective.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Their lighter weight and smaller crew requirement allowed them to be used on smaller ships than would otherwise be needed to fire such heavy projectiles.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] It was used from the mid-18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The Paixhans gun (French: *Canon Paixhans*) was the first naval gun using explosive shells.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] It was developed by French general Henri-Joseph Paixhans in 1822–1823 by combining the flat trajectory of a gun with an explosive shell that could rip apart and set on fire the bulkheads of enemy warships.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The Paixhans gun ultimately doomed the wooden sail-ship, and forced the introduction of the ironclad after the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Solid spherical cast-iron shot, the standard fare in naval battles.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Cans filled with dozens of musket balls.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The cans broke open on firing to turn the gun into a giant shotgun for use against enemy personnel.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Canvas-wrapped stacks of smaller round shot which fitted in the barrel, typically three or more layers of three.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Some grape shot was made with thin metal or wood disks between the layers, held together by a central bolt.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The packages broke open when fired and the balls scattered with deadly effect.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Grape was often used against the enemy quarterdeck to kill or injure the officers, or against enemy boarding parties.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Two iron balls joined together with a chain.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Two balls or hemispheres joined by a solid bar.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Bar shot connected by a telescoping bar which extended upon firing.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A series of long chain links which unfolded and extended upon firing.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Bags of any junk (scrap metal, bolts, rocks, gravel, old musket balls, etc.) fired to injure enemy crews.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A thick dartlike incendiary projectile with a barbed point, wrapped with pitch-soaked canvas which took fire when the gun was fired.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The point stuck in sails, hulls, or spars and set fire to the enemy ship.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Shore forts sometimes heated iron shot red-hot in a special furnace before loading it (with water-soaked wads to prevent it from setting off the powder charge prematurely).
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] The hot shot lodging in a ship's dry timbers would set the ship afire.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Because of the danger of fire aboard, heated shot were seldom used aboard ships.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] A variation on heated shot, where molten metal from a furnace is poured into a hollowed out shell and then allowed to cool briefly to seal the molten metal in before firing.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Two round shot or other projectiles loaded in one gun and fired at the same time.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] range; that is, when ships drew close enough for a pistol shot to reach between the two ships.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] To avoid bursting the gun, reduced powder charges were used.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Guns sometimes were double-shotted with canister or grape on top of ball, or even triple-shotted with very small powder charges which still were enough to cause horrible wounds at close range.
[src:naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail/naval-artillery-in-the-age-of-sail] Ammunition that worked like a grenade, exploding and sending shrapnel everywhere, either by a burning fuse which was cut to a calculated length depending on the range, or (after 1861) on contact with the target.
